Problem statement: The aim of this project is to predict a song popularity based on its lyrics. In simple terms, X would be songs lyrics, plain text written in English, and target label would be songs popularity. We've chosen the dataset from kaggle, https://www.kaggle.com/code/nuyangrai/spotify-songs-analysis. Firstly, we would try to explore data to gain insights. Secondly, we preprocess lyrics with the help of different NLP techniques. Thirdly, we create an embedding layer using glove 50d. Eventually, we build NN models with LSTM and Dense layers and try to play with different activation functions and hyper parameters to examine how the accuracy of the model, which is calculated by RMSE, would differentiate.¶

In [50]:
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def preprocess_lyrics(lyrics):
    '''remove stop words and all extra characters from lyrics'''
    lyrics = lyrics.lower()
    lyrics = re.sub('n\'t', ' not', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'s', ' is', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'m', ' am', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'ll', ' will', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'re', ' are', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'d', ' would', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('\'', '', lyrics)
    lyrics = re.sub('[^a-z\s]',' ', lyrics) #removes any character rather than a-z and white space from text
    lyrics = re.sub('\s+', ' ', lyrics) #converts any more than one space to one space
    lyrics = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(word) for word in lyrics.split() if word not in stop_words]
    lyrics = ' '.join(lyrics)
    return lyrics

X_test = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_test)

Pad Sequencing¶

In [62]:
# using pad sequencing to make the length of the inputs equal, necessary for training models
vocab_size = len(tokenizer.word_index) + 1

maxlen = 300
trunc_type='post'
padding_type='post'

X_train = pad_sequences(X_train, padding = padding_type, maxlen = maxlen, truncating = trunc_type)
X_test = pad_sequences(X_test, padding = padding_type, maxlen = maxlen, truncating = trunc_type)

Embedding dictionary using 50 dimensional glove¶

In [63]:
# creating embedding layer using glove 50 dimensional dictionary
embeddings_dictionary = dict()
glove_file = open(r'Downloads/DL1/Moe DL1/Project/glove.6B.50d.txt', encoding="utf8")

for line in glove_file:
    records = line.split()
    word = records[0]
    vector_dimensions = np.asarray(records[1:], dtype = 'float32')
    embeddings_dictionary[word] = vector_dimensions
    
glove_file.close()
In [64]:
embedding_matrix = np.zeros((vocab_size, 50))
for word, index in tokenizer.word_index.items():
    embedding_vector = embeddings_dictionary.get(word)
    if embedding_vector is not None:
        embedding_matrix[index] = embedding_vector

Building Models¶

In [65]:
# first model
# 4 hidden layers
# output layer has only 1 node which is going to calculate the song popularity 

model1 = Sequential()
embedding_layer = Embedding(vocab_size, 50, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=maxlen , trainable=False)

model1.add(embedding_layer)   #hidden1, the Embedding layer, takes the input data and converts it into dense vectors of fixed size
model1.add(LSTM(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.L1(0.01), return_sequences=True)) #hidden2: LSTM, 32 nodes and relu as activation function. adding L1 regularization
model1.add(LSTM(32, activation='relu'))                                                                             #hidden3: LSTM, 32 nodes and relu as activation function
model1.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))                                                                            #hidden4: Dense, 16 nodes and relu as activation function
model1.add(Dense(1, activation= 'relu' ))                                                                           #output: Dense, 1 nodes and relu as activation function 

model1.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'mean_squared_error', metrics = [tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()])#adam as the optimizer and mse to calculate loss function

In [69]:
# model2 with drop out which is a regularization technique to prevent overfitting
# drop out forces the model to learn multiple independent representations of the input data by randomly sets a portion of the activations, here 70%, from the previous layer to zero
# 4 hidden layers
# output layer has only 1 node which is going to calculate the song popularity 

model2_do = Sequential()
embedding_layer = Embedding(vocab_size, 50, weights=[embedding_matrix], input_length=maxlen , trainable=False)

model2_do.add(embedding_layer)                                    #hidden1, the Embedding layer, takes the input data and converts it into dense vectors of fixed size
model2_do.add(LSTM(16, activation='tanh', return_sequences=True)) #hidden2: LSTM, 16 nodes and tanh as activation function
model2_do.add(Dropout(0.7))
model2_do.add(LSTM(16, activation='tanh'))                        #hidden3: LSTM, 16 nodes and tanh as activation function
model2_do.add(Dropout(0.7))
model2_do.add(Dense(8, activation='tanh'))                        #hidden4: Dense, 8 nodes and tanh as activation function
model2_do.add(Dropout(0.6))
model2_do.add(Dense(1, activation= 'relu' ))                      #output: Dense, 1 nodes and relu as activation function

model2_do.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'mean_squared_error', metrics = [tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()]) #adam as the optimizer and mse to calculate loss function
